(42, 7, 20, 42, 7, 19, 19, 'Art thou he that should come? or look we for another?', 'John''s Inquiry to Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize John''s question to Jesus, asking, ''Art thou he that should come? or look we for another?'' This connection highlights the continuity of John''s doubt and the search for confirmation of Jesus'' identity.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 21, 41, 3, 10, 10, NULL, 'Healing Miracles of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the healing acts of Jesus, specifically mentioning his ability to cure those with plagues. This connection highlights the widespread impact of his miracles, as many sought to touch him for healing.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 21, 11, 8, 37, 37, NULL, 'Healing and Plagues Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of healing from various afflictions. Luke 7:21 mentions curing infirmities and plagues, while 1 Kings 8:37 lists various plagues and sicknesses, highlighting the need for divine intervention in times of distress.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 21, 19, 90, 7, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Healing and Wrath', 'This connection highlights the contrast between physical healing and spiritual affliction. While Luke 7:21 speaks of curing infirmities and giving sight, Psalms 90:7-9 reflects on the troubles caused by divine anger and iniquities.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 21, 40, 4, 23, 23, NULL, 'Healing Ministry of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' healing activities among the people, highlighting his role in curing sickness and disease. Luke mentions curing ''many of their infirmities,'' while Matthew states he healed ''all manner of sickness and all manner of disease.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 21, 41, 5, 29, 29, 'plagues', 'Healing of Infirmities and Plagues', 'Both passages emphasize healing from plagues, with Luke mentioning ''infirmities and plagues'' and Mark describing a woman healed of ''that plague.'' This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' miraculous healing power.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 21, 46, 11, 30, 32, NULL, 'Connection of Healing and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing and its relationship to spiritual condition. Both passages address physical ailments, with Luke mentioning cures and 1 Corinthians discussing weakness and sickness as consequences of spiritual neglect.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 21, 58, 12, 6, 6, NULL, 'Connection of Healing and Chastening', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine intervention in both passages. Luke 7:21 describes Jesus healing and restoring, while Hebrews 12:6 emphasizes God''s discipline as a form of love, suggesting that both healing and chastening are acts of care from God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 22, 23, 35, 5, 6, NULL, 'Healing and Restoration Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous healing of the blind, lame, and deaf. This connection highlights the fulfillment of prophetic signs associated with the coming of the Messiah.', 'theme', 0.657, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 22, 23, 61, 1, 3, 'to the poor the gospel is preached', 'Healing and Good News Connection', 'Both passages emphasize healing and proclaiming good news. Luke 7:22 mentions the blind seeing and the poor receiving the gospel, which parallels Isaiah 61:1-3''s focus on preaching good tidings and binding up the brokenhearted.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 22, 42, 4, 18, 18, NULL, 'Connection of Healing and Preaching', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of the blind and the preaching to the poor. This connection highlights the continuity of Jesus'' mission as described in Luke.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 22, 59, 2, 5, 5, 'to the poor the gospel is preached', 'Connection of the Poor and Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the poor. In Luke, the gospel is preached to the poor, while James highlights that God has chosen the poor rich in faith.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 22, 40, 9, 28, 30, 'the blind see', 'Healing and Faith Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of the blind, showcasing Jesus'' miraculous abilities. In Luke, Jesus mentions the blind seeing as part of his ministry, while in Matthew, he directly heals blind men, affirming their faith.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 22, 40, 15, 30, 31, 'the blind see, the lame walk', 'Healing Miracles of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus healing the blind, lame, and deaf. They highlight the miraculous works of Jesus and the response of the people to these healings.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 22, 42, 7, 14, 15, 'the dead are raised', 'Miracles of Healing and Resurrection', 'This connection highlights the miracles performed by Jesus, specifically the raising of the dead in both passages. Both emphasize the transformative power of Jesus, as seen in the phrases ''the dead are raised'' and ''Young man, I say unto thee, Arise.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 23, 23, 8, 14, 15, 'not be offended in me', 'Connection of Offense in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being ''offended'' by Jesus. Isaiah describes Him as a ''rock of offence,'' while Luke pronounces a blessing on those who are not offended in Him.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 23, 40, 11, 6, 6, 'blessed is he, whosoever shall not be offended in me', 'Blessed is He Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''blessed is he, whosoever shall not be offended in me,'' highlighting a shared message about faith and acceptance. This connection underscores the importance of not being offended by Jesus'' teachings.', 'keyword', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 23, 45, 9, 32, 33, 'whosoever shall not be offended in me', 'Blessed and Stumblingstone Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief and offense. Both passages emphasize that those who believe will not be ashamed or offended, contrasting faith with the stumbling over the law.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 23, 60, 2, 7, 8, 'not be offended in me', 'Blessedness and Offense in Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of being offended by Christ. In Luke 7:23, those who are not offended are blessed, while 1 Peter 2:8 speaks of Christ as a ''rock of offence'' to the disobedient.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 23, 40, 13, 57, 58, 'offended in me', 'Offense and Unbelief in Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of being offended by Jesus. Both passages emphasize the response of people to Jesus, where those who are offended demonstrate unbelief, impacting His works among them.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 23, 42, 2, 34, 34, 'blessed is he, whosoever shall not be offended in me', 'Blessing and Opposition Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being blessed amidst opposition. Luke 7:23 speaks of those who are not offended, while Luke 2:34 mentions a child who will be a sign spoken against.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 23, 43, 6, 60, 66, 'blessed is he, whosoever shall not be offended in me', 'Offense and Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being offended by Jesus'' teachings. In Luke, Jesus blesses those who are not offended in him, while in John, some disciples express offense at his words and choose to leave. This connection highlights the challenge of accepting Jesus'' message.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 24, 49, 4, 14, 14, 'a reed shaken with the wind', 'Connection of Instability and Deception', 'This connection highlights the theme of instability in faith. Both passages emphasize being ''tossed to and fro'' and not being swayed by external influences, whether they be ''a reed shaken with the wind'' or ''every wind of doctrine.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 24, 42, 1, 80, 80, 'the wilderness', 'Connection of John the Baptist''s Wilderness', 'Both passages emphasize John''s presence in the wilderness, highlighting his role as a prophet. Luke 1:80 notes his time in the deserts, while Luke 7:24 questions the people''s expectations of him, suggesting he was not easily swayed like ''a reed shaken with the wind.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
